    frank.wage += 5000.0;

    // Today is Joe's birthday
    ++joe.age; // use pre-increment to increment Joe's age by 1

    return 0;
}In the above example, it is very easy to tell which member variables belong to Joe and which belong to Frank. This provides a much higher level of organization than individual variables would. Furthermore, because Joe’s and Frank’s members have the same names, this provides consistency when you have multiple variables of the same struct type.We’ll continue our exploration of structs in the next lesson, including a look at how to initialize them.Next lesson13.8Struct aggregate initializationBack to table of contentsPrevious lesson13.6Scoped enumerations (enum classes)

